@node SYSCHAL "The OLFB Sysop Challenge"

 * NEW * as of OLFB ver 2.0

 Online FootBall Now allows the caller to challenge the sysop
 one on one, head to head, live, may the best man win !

 How it works :

  When a caller selects the option to challenge the sysop, the Sysop
  will here a guitar sound (Assuming your sound is on). The sound
  can be any SoungFile you like as long as you name it OLFB.sound
  and put it in your OLFB dir.

  If you want to Accept the challenge and play against the caller,
  (and assuming you have OLFB set up correctly) type "ACCEPTCHAL"
  in a CLI window, or have it in a menu or hotkey as you prefer.
  If you don't wanna play, ignore it..

  Once you've accepted the challenge, you'll be entered into the
  OLFB Chat mode.. Here, you can introduce yourself, and try to
  raz the caller if ya like.. Break outta chat by typing
  "Q" on a new line.

  From that point, everything will be quite obvious. You will
  both enter your play selections when prompted, and neither
  player will be able to see the others entries.

  * Attention *

  Two things that I became aware of while testing the Sysop Challenge.

  1. A caller who wanted to cheat, could try to enter the plays
     for the Sysop. (My brother-in-law always cheats)

  2. Callers using an IBM can see the plays entered, even though
     the AMIGA sysop can't. (This is due to the way the IBM
     uses ANSI)

  I was able to fix these problems for BBBBS, CNET, and E! by using
  special commands that these systems provide.

  For everyone else (and the above also, if you'd rather) I've provided
  an option for a "Popup" window to accept OLFB input whenever
  it's the sysops turn, effectively locking out the caller from
  seeing your entry or trying to enter it himself..

  To activate this Feature, create a file in your OLFB dir
  named "OLFB.screen". (A working example for BBBBS systems is
  provided in this archive.)

  The file should have three lines in it as follows:

BAUD
100
100

  This first line is the public screen name where you want the
  Popup window to appear. (Supposedly your BBS screen)

  How do I know my public screen name? > @{"Read me" link GETSCREEN}

      +&+&+&+&

  For CNET Systems this line should read         CNETSCREEN
  OLFB will decide which port is being used.

      +&+&+&+&

  The second line is the X factor for the top left corner of the
  Popup window. Adjust to your preferences.

  The third line is the Y factor for the top left corner of the
  Popup window. Adjust to your preferences.

  That's it, once this file exists, this feature will be active.

@endnode

@node GETSCREEN "How do I know what my BBS's public screen name is?"

  The easiest way to find your public screen name is by looking
  in the docs supplied with your BBS software.

  I have supplied a small Arexx script with this archive named
  "GetScreen.rexx". Combined with "getPubName.lha" you will
  be able to find your BBS's public screen name if it has one.

  GetPubName.lha is FreeWare & Copyright 1992 by Michael `Mick' Hohmann
  It is available for DL at The Alternative BBS (503)761-8024
  and many other Amiga BBS's.

  Once you have "getPubName.lha" follow the instructions inside
  of "GetScreen.rexx" to find your Public Screen name.

@endnode

